<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-523-309  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 523 309.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 22 1990 v24 n43 p25(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Finally coming into its own: reverse engineering technology makesheadway into IS organizations. (includes related article onre-engineering and reverse engineering tools)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ambrosio, Johanna.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Because the re-engineering and reverse engineering markets arestill in their inchoate stages, users must rely on multiple toolsfrom multiple vendors.andP;  Definitions of the two terms have not yetbeen settled, but re-engineering is generally held to meanmodularizing and restructuring the 'spaghetti' code of existingapplications.andP;  Reverse engineering goes one step farther: the dataand process definitions are extracted from existing applications,stored in a repository, and then use to create new code for theapplications.andP;  The two techniques can save maintenance costs anddrastically cut code lineage, but convincing top management oftheir value is often a tough job.andP;  At present, re-engineering andreverse engineering tools are available only for Cobol programs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Software EngineeringReverse EngineeringProgram Development ToolsProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Identifying business needs lies at the heart of reverseengineering. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>